WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.960
The land down under is best known for its vast&nbsp;
and remote outback covering most of the country's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:10.720
interior. While in reality it is covering&nbsp;
climatic zones ranging from tropical to temperate,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:16.160
it is best known for its arid center, where the&nbsp;
most extreme landscapes of Australia are forming a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:23.360
mosaic of salt and red earths, collectively called&nbsp;
the Great Australian Desert. What may seem like a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:28.560
whole lot of nothingness, is actually a continent&nbsp;
sized system that runs on brief violent pulses of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:34.000
water, ancient aquifers moving in million year&nbsp;
cycles and explosions of colors where you would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:39.200
least expect them. To better understand this&nbsp;
enormous system, in this video we will first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:43.920
get some general context on the most arid parts&nbsp;
of Australia, before traversing half the continent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:50.560
to see how these deserts actually work.
Chapter 1) Origins of the Australian Desert&nbsp;

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:54.000
First of all, we need to clear up the&nbsp;
misconception of the Great Australian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:59.520
Desert. When searching for a list of the largest&nbsp;
deserts by area, the so-called “Great Australian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:04.800
Desert” often takes the 5th spot after the&nbsp;
poles, the Sahara and the Arabian Desert,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:09.760
but this isn’t entirely correct. Geographically&nbsp;
speaking, there isn’t really a single entity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:15.200
called the “Great Australian Desert” but instead a&nbsp;
collection of 10 deserts that follow the framework&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:19.760
and limits of the “Interim Biogeographic&nbsp;
Regionalisations for Australia”, that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:24.720
informally make up the great Australian desert.
These 10 deserts are largely organized into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:29.840
an eastern and western cluster, but while I have&nbsp;
drawn clear borders between the constituents here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:34.640
they are a little bit more fuzzy in reality.&nbsp;
Deserts are commonly defined not by heat,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:40.640
but by water balance with the rule of thumb that&nbsp;
any area receiving less than 250 millimeters of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:46.400
rain per year is considered a desert. This rule&nbsp;
however, doesn’t capture many edge cases so the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:52.240
concept of an aridity index is sometimes used&nbsp;
instead. That index is simply rainfall divided&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:57.600
by the atmosphere’s drying power, meaning how&nbsp;
much water could evaporate given temperature,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:03.200
sun, humidity, and wind, and in deserts&nbsp;
this index is typically below 0.2.&nbsp;

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:08.000
In the case of our Australian Desert, these&nbsp;
criteria are always met in the core of each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.760
desert, but become less precise around the&nbsp;
margins. Further, unlike deserts like the Sahara&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:19.760
or Arabian Desert, the Australian Deserts can be&nbsp;
a lot more erratic. Sudden cloud bursts can exceed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:24.960
the precipitation threshold in a single day,&nbsp;
while other years see no precipitation at all.&nbsp;

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:28.880
The transition zones from one desert to&nbsp;
another are also not as precise as I have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:34.080
drawn here. Instead, it is an approximation,&nbsp;
aggregating various different sources,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:39.680
that use dominant landforms, vegetation and&nbsp;
drainage patterns to distinguish between the deserts.&nbsp;

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:44.960
Besides the “where”, we should also clarify the&nbsp;
why, since many other regions in the world at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:50.480
same latitude are covered in lush forests. The&nbsp;
foremost reason for aridity in Australia's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:56.480
heart is its general position on the globe. Placed&nbsp;
between the 25° and 35° latitude, the Australian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.480 --> 00:03:01.680
deserts lie right below a global high pressure&nbsp;
zone around the Tropics of Capricorn. Warm air&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:07.520
over the equator expels most of its moisture as it&nbsp;
rises and cools down, before traveling southwards.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:12.880
As the air sinks again over the subtropical ridge,&nbsp;
the warming air loses relative humidity, leading&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:18.800
to dry air arriving over the Australian continent.
Further, the West Australian current, as part of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:24.400
the Antarctic circulation, brings cold waters&nbsp;
to Australia’s western coast, preventing any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:29.120
significant evaporation from collecting&nbsp;
in the coastal regions. And on the east,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:34.160
the Great Dividing Range enhances rainfall&nbsp;
on the coastal side and can reduce moisture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:39.200
penetration inland, contributing to a sharp&nbsp;
wet-to-dry gradient across the continent.&nbsp;

00:03:39.200 --> 00:03:44.000
The combination of all of these factors make the&nbsp;
continent of Australia the second driest continent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:49.600
on the planet after the Antarctic ice desert, but&nbsp;
within these harsh conditions, also lie a lot of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:54.320
geographical peculiarities which we will travel&nbsp;
through from the west to the east, bringing us to&nbsp;

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:58.640
Chapter 2) The western desert
Starting just behind the coast of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:58.640 --> 00:04:04.320
the Dampierland, lies the Great Sandy Desert,&nbsp;
the first of 5 deserts in this larger cluster.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:09.120
Right off the bat, it boasts some of the highest&nbsp;
temperatures of Australia, which pushes against&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:14.000
the slightly higher precipitation than what you&nbsp;
would typically see in a desert. The average of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.480
300 millimeters of rain that falls annually can&nbsp;
be a bit misleading though, since this region&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:23.440
is known for some of the most erratic weather.
The most extreme region in the north experiences&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:28.400
30 to 40 localized thunderstorms annually, yet&nbsp;
some storms drop little or no measurable rain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:33.200
at the surface since the hot climate evaporates&nbsp;
any moisture before it reaches the ground in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:37.440
process called virga. The weather is not&nbsp;
just erratic on an annual basis though,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:42.800
and decade long shifts can completely transform&nbsp;
entire regions. Looking at the weather station at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:48.160
Territory Grape Farm in the Northern Territory&nbsp;
for example, in 1925 precipitation measurements&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:56.000
yielded 25 millimeters of annual rain, while in&nbsp;
1974, this figure skyrocketed to 955 mm, just to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.360
average back down to 310 mm since the 1990s.
When the water does make it through though,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:06.640
it can often lead to flash floods that submerge&nbsp;
the interdune corridors in a blanket of water,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:11.520
kicking off an incredible but short-lived&nbsp;
circle of life. Dormant seeds are shooting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.520 --> 00:05:16.960
out of the ground to form wildflower fields&nbsp;
while insect populations explode and birds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:22.320
start breeding. Water collects in dozens of&nbsp;
small drainage basins across the western desert,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:27.520
just to disappear again a few days to weeks after&nbsp;
the most severe rainfall, leading to the flora and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:31.440
fauna slipping back into dormancy.
Where the dune seas give way to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:36.560
vegetation, hummock grasses are among the few&nbsp;
plants tough enough to hold on. But in parts of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:41.680
the Great Victoria Desert, even that disappears.
This region of Australia is one of the most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:47.200
tectonically stable, meaning that eroding forces&nbsp;
like wind and water had a lot of time to act upon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:52.480
the same surfaces. While it is not particularly&nbsp;
windy in the Great Victoria Desert, consistency&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:57.520
does the job as well, so in certain areas, nearly&nbsp;
all fine material has been stripped away, leaving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.520 --> 00:06:02.480
nothing but virtually never ending pebble fields.&nbsp;
These formations are called desert pavement or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:07.920
gibber fields and while scientists still debate&nbsp;
the details of how fast they form and which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:13.680
processes dominate in different places, it is&nbsp;
clear why vegetation has a hard time growing here.&nbsp;

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:18.880
Another habitat that is almost devoid of life are&nbsp;
the hundreds of ephemeral lakes scattered around&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:24.000
western deserts. Being filled by the short bursts&nbsp;
of rain, most of these lakes are dried for most of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:30.320
the year, exposing their reflective salt pans and&nbsp;
organic residue that is left after evaporation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:34.240
The largest of these lake basins can cover&nbsp;
hundreds of kilometers in width and length,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:39.360
though the concept of shoreline is a bit arbitrary&nbsp;
here. The salt crusts and sediment deposits have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:44.000
flattened out the basins to such an extent that&nbsp;
a few centimeters of water can create a water&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.560
coverage of hundreds of square kilometers and&nbsp;
satellite imagery can be quite misleading in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:53.200
trying to identify water coverage. Clay&nbsp;
rich surfaces can look dark and wet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:57.360
despite the absence of water, and pools&nbsp;
on white salt beds can imitate a dry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.360 --> 00:07:01.520
surface while they are actually submerged.
These mirage forming nature spectacles are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:07.200
not limited to the western deserts though. As we cross a&nbsp;
semi-arid corridor of plains and mountains to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:12.400
east, we are once again greeted by something even&nbsp;
stranger. Before we step into this vast landscape&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:17.680
of ephemeral streams and enormous ancient aquifers&nbsp;
though, let’s take a step back and zoom out for a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:22.960
bit. The Australian deserts we’ve seen&nbsp;
so far are only a small fraction of the earth’s dryland,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:26.800
