Chapter 3) The eastern deserts&nbsp;

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:18.640
Separated by a series of semi-arid ecoregions&nbsp;
like the Stony Plains, Finke, MacDonnell Ranges&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:24.800
and the Burt Plains to the east, a cluster of 5 
more deserts are covering the centermost outback.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:30.320
The storm driven boom-bust ecosystems of dunes and&nbsp;
gibber fields now transition to a somewhat calmer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:36.160
ecosystem that is shaped by large ephemeral&nbsp;
rivers and the largest aquifer on the planet.&nbsp;

00:08:36.160 --> 00:08:41.760
Spanning 1.7 million square kilometers, roughly&nbsp;
the size of Alaska or countries like Mongolia&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:47.760
or Iran, the Great Artesian Basin underlies&nbsp;
22% of Australia and is a vital lifeline for 

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:52.640
the Continent. Alternating layers of porous&nbsp;
sandstone and watertight shale or mudstone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:57.840
are forming lens shaped bowls reaching from the&nbsp;
great dividing range to the heart of the outback,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:03.680
trapping groundwater in million year long cycles.
From the highest elevations of New South Wales,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:09.200
the aquifer reaches up to 3.000 meters into the&nbsp;
ground, and water which enters the exposed porous&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:14.160
layers in the mountains can take up to 2 million&nbsp;
years until it reaches the westernmost extent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.160 --> 00:09:19.200
under the deserts. Here, natural springs&nbsp;
and seeps, cracks in the impermeable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:25.200
layers, press the water to the surface, where a&nbsp;
series of surface streams define the landscape.&nbsp;

00:09:25.200 --> 00:09:30.720
Between the 5 deserts of the eastern cluster,&nbsp;
the Cooper Creek, Diamantina, Georgina and Finke&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:36.000
rivers all funnel waters from Australia’s largest&nbsp;
drainage basin into the epitome of Australian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:42.160
salt lakes. Lying above the Tirari Desert in the&nbsp;
center of the eastern cluster, the Kati Thanda,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:47.840
formerly known as Lake Eyre is the lowest point of&nbsp;
the Australian continent at 15m below sea level,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:52.960
and the final destination of these waters.
All of these streams are ephemeral rivers, meaning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:58.320
they run only when favourable conditions line&nbsp;
up. Most years they’re chains of dry channels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:03.680
waterholes, and flats, but after big rains in the&nbsp;
wider catchment area, they switch on and behave&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:08.400
less like a normal river network and more like&nbsp;
a pulse-driven wetland system fighting against&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:09.850
the continental aridity.

00:10:09.947 --> 00:10:11.600
Despite these sources of water in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:17.680
the largest drainage basin of the continent, water&nbsp;
reaches the Kati Thanda only on rare occasions.&nbsp;

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:21.360
Exceptional rain bursts are necessary&nbsp;
to create a blanket of water on the salt&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.360 --> 00:10:26.160
pans and in these instances, not just&nbsp;
the Kati Thanda but the drainage basin&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:31.360
as a whole is transformed in its entirety.&nbsp;
The shallow river courses easily overflow,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:31.360 --> 00:10:36.480
creating vast wetland regions which make the&nbsp;
whole basin explode with color and life. Lush&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:42.160
green grass patches, scattered with wild flowers&nbsp;
and the white and pink hues of salt and sediments&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:42.160 --> 00:10:46.160
create one of the most vivid pictures mother&nbsp;
nature has to offer, right in the otherwise&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:50.400
barren deserts of the eastern cluster.
Even during times of flooding however,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:56.080
Kati Thanda barely fills to its maximum extent.&nbsp;
Since surveys began in the 19th century, there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:56.080 --> 00:11:00.880
have only been three instances where the salt pan&nbsp;
of the lake is filled completely, connecting the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:07.120
two major basins into one continuous system. In&nbsp;
these instances, which last occurred in 1974,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:12.480
the lake still only reaches a depth of around&nbsp;
6 meter or 20 feet at its deepest levels and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:17.840
with evaporation rates of up to 3.5 meter per&nbsp;
year, it is always a short lived spectacle.&nbsp;

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:23.520
In 2025, after years of drought, Kati Thanda&nbsp;
finally filled again as is visualized in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:28.400
photo series created by NASA’s Terra Satellite,&nbsp;
and the impacts on wildlife have been truly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:32.880
exceptional. Brine shrimp eggs which have&nbsp;
been dormant in the soil for years suddenly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:37.520
come to life, and where floodwaters&nbsp;
persist, fish follow, and then pelicans,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:42.560
banded stilts and many other bird species&nbsp;
join the feast. Once the wetlands fade again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:47.600
the dire salt crusts quickly return, and the&nbsp;
fauna that was thriving in abundance now has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:52.880
to seek refuge in the Mound Springs of the Great&nbsp;
Artesian Basin, waiting for the cycle to repeat.&nbsp;

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:57.520
Overall the ten deserts that make up the broader&nbsp;
Great Australian Desert live in a constant&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:03.200
anticipation of new water. Whether it be through&nbsp;
brief erratic violent storms and flashfloods, or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:03.200 --> 00:12:08.320
ancient groundwater with temporary rivers fighting&nbsp;
to complete their course, these biological pulses&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:14.240
are an immaculate example of natural systems&nbsp;
existing on the edge of what is possible.&nbsp;

00:12:14.240 --> 00:12:19.200
If you want to see the other side of the Australian
water story, the Murray-Darling Basin is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:23.920
perfect opposite. A temperate river system not&nbsp;
challenged by nature’s constraints but instead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:28.480
by human challenges. You can find that video&nbsp;
here, or watch what YouTube thinks is best for&nbsp;&nbsp;

